		<part id="past">
			<title short="The Past">The Past: A Brief History of API Management</title>
			<slide id="big-bang">
				<title>Information Management: A Proposal</title>
				<img src="information-management-proposal.jpg" href="https://home.cern/science/computing/birth-web/short-history-web" title='Tim Berners-Lee: "Information Management: A Proposal", March 1989' class="fullsize-shadow" />
			</slide>
			<slide id="">
				<title>From the Human Web to the Machine Web</title>
				<ul>
					<li>1990: First server at CERN</li>
					<li>1993: NCSA releases Mosaic browser</li>
					<li>1998: Extensible Markup Language (XML)</li>
					<li>2000: SOAP</li>
					<li>2000: "Internet as a Service": Salesforce, eBay, Amazon</li>
					<li>2003: "Building Blocks": Delicious, Flickr, Facebook, Twitter, Foursquare, Twilio</li>
				</ul>
			</slide>
			<slide id="forward-proxy">
				<title>Forward Proxy: Shielding Clients</title>
				<img source='UpGuard Blog: "What is a Reverse Proxy Server?"' src="proxy-forward.png" href="https://www.upguard.com/blog/what-is-a-reverse-proxy" class="fullsize" />
			</slide>
			<slide id="forward-proxy">
				<title>Reverse Proxy: Shielding Servers</title>
				<img source='UpGuard Blog: "What is a Reverse Proxy Server?"' src="proxy-reverse.png" href="https://www.upguard.com/blog/what-is-a-reverse-proxy" class="fullsize" />
			</slide>
			<slide id="api-management-technical">
				<title>Securing APIs</title>
				<img src="API-management-technical.png" class="fullsize-shadow"/>
			</slide>
			<slide id="proxy">
				<title>Securing <q>Public</q> Interfaces</title>
				<ul>
					<li>API management started from the web's <q>reverse proxy</q> model</li>
					<li>Resources should be made available while minimizing risks</li>
					<li>API-specific functions started showing up (e.g., XMLâ†”JSON)</li>
				</ul>
			</slide>
			<slide id="api-management-lifecycle">
				<title>Supporting the API Lifecycle</title>
				<img src="API-management-lifecycle.png" class="fullsize-shadow"/>
			</slide>
			<slide id="lifecycle-tooling">
				<title>API Tooling</title>
				<ul>
					<li>Going beyond <q>just</q> protecting the operational API</li>
					<li>The <q>API lifecycle</q> supports the whole API development process</li>
					<ul>
						<li><em>Design</em> with support for following guidelines</li>
						<li><em>Mocking</em> to quickly allow consumers to start developing</li>
						<li><em>Documentation</em> to make the API easy to use for everyone</li>
						<li><em>Testing</em> to make sure the API works as intended</li>
						<li><em>Monitoring</em> to understand use and detect misuse</li>
					</ul>
				</ul>
			</slide>
			<slide id="api-management-product">
				<title>APIs as Business Building Blocks</title>
				<img src="API-management-product.png" class="fullsize-shadow"/>
			</slide>
			<slide id="products">
				<title>Shifting to a Product Focus</title>
				<ul>
					<li>Growing API landscapes mean growing complexity</li>
					<li>Focus on API value over API implementation</li>
					<li>Decoupling technical management from business value makes sense</li>
				</ul>
			</slide>
			<slide id="api-management-marketing">
				<title>API Consumption Matters</title>
				<img src="API-management-marketing.png" class="fullsize-shadow"/>
			</slide>
			<slide id="api-marketing">
				<title>Having APIs isn't Good Enough</title>
				<ul>
					<li>APIs only provide value when they being consumed</li>
					<li><em>API Marketing</em> makes sure to get the most out of API products</li>
					<li>Increase adoption by decoupling production and marketing</li>
				</ul>
			</slide>
		</part>
